     1	# Perf gates — the two-tier model
     2	
     3	FathomDB has **two** perf-gate tiers that exercise the *same* production read
     4	path (`Engine::search` → FTS5 MATCH + two-phase bit-KNN + f32 rerank) at
     5	different scales, with different jobs:
     6	
     7	| Tier | File | Runs | N | Job |
     8	|---|---|---|---|---|
     9	| **Devloop** | `crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates_devloop.rs` | always, in `cargo test` | ≈1000 | fast inner-loop signal (seconds) |
    10	| **Canonical** | `crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs` | `AGENT_LONG=1` only | 10k binding / 100k / 1M | ship verdict |
    11	
    12	The devloop tier is the subject of 0.7.2 PR-6. The canonical tier is the
    13	ADR-locked release verdict (PR-3); this doc explains how the two relate so a
    14	green devloop run is never mistaken for a ship verdict (or vice versa).
    15	
    16	---
    17	
    18	## Why two tiers
    19	
    20	The canonical gates are slow: the real-embedder N=1M measurement is infeasible
    21	on CI (~166 h of serialized BGE seed; see
    22	`dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-3-output.json`), so they are `AGENT_LONG`-gated and run
    23	as a once-per-release local exercise. That leaves the inner dev loop with **no
    24	perf signal at all** between releases — a latency or vector-wiring regression
    25	could land and sit unnoticed until the next canonical run.
    26	
    27	The devloop tier fills that gap: a ≈1000-doc subset (via PR-5's `CorpusFixture`)
    28	that runs on every `cargo test`, exercises the identical production read SQL,
    29	and surfaces a perf + recall + structural signal in ~16 s.
    30	
    31	It does **not** replace the canonical verdict. Small-N latency is noisy and the
    32	synthetic embedder cannot meet the real-data recall/stress bounds, so the
    33	devloop tier deliberately does **not** assert the canonical budgets.
    34	
    35	---
    36	
    37	## Gate disposition: notify vs block (HITL-locked 2026-06-01)
    38	
    39	The governing rule for the devloop tier is **perf signals NOTIFY, structural
    40	invariants BLOCK**:
    41	
    42	| Signal | Disposition | Catches | Why this disposition |
    43	|---|---|---|---|
    44	| `assert_vec0_row_count_matches_ingest` | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | batch-collapse (`4a95cfd`) | deterministic correctness — a collapsed batch leaves `vector_default` short of the doc count; no flap risk |
    45	| `assert_fts_index_populated` | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | FTS path not wired | deterministic correctness |
    46	| latency p50 ≤ 50 ms / p99 ≤ 150 ms (synthetic) | **notify-only WARN** | gradual latency drift | small-N sample noise should not fail `cargo test`; PR-7 turns the trend into a CI gate |
    47	| **catastrophic ceiling** p50 > 500 ms / p99 > 1500 ms (10× soft; synthetic) | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | scanner-throughput (`53a270d`) | an orders-of-magnitude inflation is unambiguously a regression, not noise |
    48	| latency (real embedder) | **report-only** | — | `search` latency on the real path is candle-embed-influenced, not a clean retrieval signal; synthetic isolates retrieval |
    49	| recall@10 ≥ 0.85 (real embedder) | **notify-only WARN** | quantization-fidelity drift | noisy at small N; PR-7 owns the trend gate |
    50	| recall@10 (synthetic embedder) | **report-only** | — | synthetic vectors quantize poorly (~0.35 @ N≈1000) — a property of the DATA, not a regression (mirrors AC-019) |
    51	
    52	**The two embedders carry complementary signals:** synthetic isolates
    53	**latency** (instant embed → measured time is pure retrieval); real makes
    54	**recall** meaningful (dense vectors → ANN fidelity is real). Each path's
    55	off-signal is report-only.
    56	
    57	### Why a single hard catastrophic ceiling
    58	
    59	Notify-only latency alone would mean the scanner-throughput regression
    60	(`53a270d`, whose symptom is orders-of-magnitude p50/p99 inflation) no longer
    61	fails `cargo test`. The catastrophic ceiling at 10× the soft budget restores a
    62	hard RED for that regression while leaving routine noise to the notify path: a
    63	regression that inflates p50 from ~14 ms to hundreds of ms clears 500 ms; normal
    64	run-to-run wobble never does.
    65	
    66	### RED-shows evidence
    67	
    68	Both named regressions were re-introduced (symptom-injected at the gate seam) in
    69	a throwaway run and confirmed to RED-fail — see
    70	`dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-6-output.json` (`red_shows_experiment`):
    71	
    72	- batch-collapse → `assert_vec0_row_count_matches_ingest` panics
    73	  (*"vector_default has 1 rows but 1000 … docs were ingested"*).
    74	- scanner-throughput → `enforce_catastrophic_ceiling` panics
    75	  (*"DEVLOOP CATASTROPHIC (013): p50=616ms > 500ms"*).
    76	
    77	---
    78	
    79	## Embedder: synthetic default, real opt-in
    80	
    81	- **Synthetic (`VaryingEmbedder`) — always-runs default.** Its embed is instant,
    82	  so the measured latency isolates *retrieval* (same rationale as canonical
    83	  AC-013). This is the inner-loop signal and the only path bound by the ≤30 s
    84	  budget. It carries the latency gates; its recall is report-only (see above).
    85	- **Real BGE — opt-in.** Enabled by `DEVLOOP_REAL_EMBEDDER=1` **and** the
    86	  `default-embedder` feature; without the feature the fixture SKIPs gracefully.
    87	  It carries the 0.85 recall-floor WARN; its latency is report-only. Cold-cache
    88	  is **allowed** (the first run warms PR-5's on-disk doc-body cache and is slow);
    89	  a warm re-run skips re-embedding doc bodies. Held-out *query* texts are not in
    90	  the doc-body cache, so the warmup pass embeds them live once (the in-memory
    91	  cache then serves the measure pass) and the recall ground-truth pass embeds
    92	  them again — so the real path's WALL time is candle-bound and **not** ≤30 s
    93	  regardless of the doc cache. It is an occasional end-to-end exercise, not the
    94	  inner-loop signal.
    95	
    96	The PR-5 embedding cache (`data/corpus-data/.cache/embeddings/`) caches embed
    97	*inputs*, not query *results*: warm runs skip re-embedding doc bodies but the
    98	production bit-KNN + f32 rerank read path runs in full every time. The devloop
    99	tests therefore measure the real read path, never a cached short-circuit.
   100	
   101	---
   102	
   103	## Knob inventory (`DEVLOOP_*`)
   104	
   105	The devloop tier keeps its own knob surface, disjoint from the canonical
   106	`AC013_*` / `AC019_*` knobs, so neither contract bleeds into the other.
   107	
   108	| Knob | Effect | Default |
   109	|---|---|---|
   110	| `DEVLOOP_REAL_EMBEDDER=1` | use real BGE (requires `default-embedder`; cold-cache allowed, warm re-run faster) | unset → synthetic |
   111	| `FATHOMDB_CORPUS_CACHE_DIR` | override the PR-5 embed-cache dir (shared with the harness) | `data/corpus-data/.cache/embeddings/` |
   112	
   113	In-code budget constants (not env): `DEVLOOP_BUDGET_P50` (50 ms),
   114	`DEVLOOP_BUDGET_P99` (150 ms), `DEVLOOP_RECALL_FLOOR` (0.85),
   115	`DEVLOOP_CATASTROPHIC_MULT` (10×), `DEVLOOP_SAMPLES` (100), `DEVLOOP_SEED`.
   116	
   117	Devloop tests are **not** gated behind `AGENT_LONG` — that flag is the canonical
   118	tier's switch and the devloop tier must run unconditionally.
   119	
   120	---
   121	
   122	## The `DEVLOOP_NUMBERS` line (PR-7 consumes this)
   123	
   124	Each test emits one stable, parseable trend line on stderr:
   125	
   126	```
   127	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=013 n=1000 samples=100 p50_ms=14 p99_ms=18 recall_at_10=NA cache=na embedder=synthetic
   128	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=013b n=1000 samples=100 p50_ms=0 p99_ms=0 recall_at_10=0.3470 cache=na embedder=synthetic
   129	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=019 n=1000 samples=200 p50_ms=12 p99_ms=154 recall_at_10=NA cache=na embedder=synthetic
   130	DEVLOOP_AC019_DETAIL ac=019 threads=4 per_thread=50 stress_ms=5728 baseline_p99_ms=16 stress_p50_ms=12 stress_p99_ms=154 disposition=report_only
   131	```
   132	
   133	All three ACs share the same keyed `DEVLOOP_NUMBERS` schema
   134	(`ac/n/samples/p50_ms/p99_ms/recall_at_10/cache/embedder`); for AC-019 the
   135	percentiles are the stress-tail. AC-019's extra detail (baseline, thread shape,
   136	wall time) is on a separate `DEVLOOP_AC019_DETAIL` line so the common contract
   137	stays uniform.
   138	
   139	Breach notifications (notify-only, do not fail):
   140	
   141	```
   142	DEVLOOP_PERF_WARN ac=013 metric=p50 value_ms=60 budget_ms=50 status=OVER
   143	DEVLOOP_PERF_WARN ac=013b metric=recall_at_10 value=0.83 floor=0.85 status=UNDER   # real embedder only
   144	DEVLOOP_PERF_INFO ac=013b metric=recall_at_10 disposition=report_only embedder=synthetic
   145	```
   146	
   147	The `ac=`, `p50_ms=`, `p99_ms=`, `recall_at_10=` fields are the stable contract
   148	**PR-7** (perf-regression detection, `dev/perf-history/`) parses to build the
   149	per-(ac, embedder) trend and apply its 10 %-latency / 0.02-recall thresholds.
   150	Adding fields is safe; renaming or reordering the keyed fields is a breaking
   151	change to that contract.
   152	
   153	---
   154	
